@Mean Old Lady 

“Chopped” is a cooking contest, not a game show. 

There are there contestants and three rounds.  A panel of judges votes after each round. One contestant is eliminated after each vote.

@Steve L 
Um, Steve, we have watched it for several YEARS.  Thanks for 'splainin,' but really....

Given the manipulative boxes, I say itis a game.

@MmmmHmmm 

There are over 170,000 words in current use. Do I (or even most of us) need to have used them all in order for them to be legitimate?

I personally like rare words in my crosswords (though aglare, aglow, agleam, etc seem more poetic than rare?), especially if the alternative is an emu in need of an oreo asap. Keeps things interesting.

@Jon 

The very funny novel and movie “Cold Comfort Farm” has a minor character named RENNET, one of the farm girls. The name is funnier if you know what RENNET is. 

I’m a bit surprised by the number of people who are unfamiliar with EPAULET. It seems like a pretty normal word to me, but then, I was a kid when “Sgt. Pepper’s Lonely Hearts Club Band” was released.

@mead absurdum 

You had mead absurdum.




Dook, dook, goose.

@Times Rita 
Of course I remember that product and thus this was a gimme for me. See this nostalgic article from the Chicago Trib about this custard from the 1960’s. If you go to junketdesserts.com you can see their current product line, which seems not to include the original custard anymore. Their website has lots of nostalgic old adds as well. Start with:

<a href="https://tinyurl.com/2p9usf6y" target="_blank">https://tinyurl.com/2p9usf6y</a>

@Hardroch 
DOOK is funny, but the constructor needed another eight-letter answer to fill the HALFTIME spot.
I would have been OK with her suggested MO ON BEAM, but agree with the editors that SO[,] UP BOWLS is not worthy.

@Bee Ostrowsky 
I agree that a sea lion doesn't sound exactly like a dog barking.  

But that's the way it's very commonly described.

@Eric Hougland 
Oh no I've been out minutiae'd!!!
But while we're on the subject: since clues of this sort don't specify that the answer word must come *directly* before or after the clue word, we can say that any word that has ever come before "box" would qualify, as would any that is yet to come after "black." This removes any hopes for a limit indeed.

@Asher B. 

You have to assume that “before” or “after” in this kind of clue implies a “directly.”

They can be challenging clues in any case, much as a Fill in the Blank clue can be a gimme or a poser.

@Nick 

Gee, that's an awfully weird thing to say.  Is big beef pushing PRIME RIB on us?



Is prime emu even a thing?

@DDW 

Please know that the puzzle launched last night, before the article came out this morning about these former officers and their heinous crimes.

An unfortunate coincidence, but a coincidence nonetheless.

@Fender what Bubba said. It has stood (and probably still can stand) for both. I definitely learned it as “questioning” when I was first exposed to the term LGBTQ, but I can’t say if the Q has always stood for both or if “queer” came later. For sure the term “queer” was previously a slur, but was re-appropriated by the LGBTQ community, so maybe that word was later attached to that letter once “queer” became more mainstream as a term of pride rather than a slur. 

I think the A in LGBTQIA+ can also stand for a more than one thing (asexual or aromantic, but also ally) 😊

